<TITLE> India slump after Ryder's double century </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAPIER, New Zealand, Mar 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - India slumped to 79 for three in reply to New Zealand's mammoth 619 for nine declared led by Jesse Ryder's double century on the second day of the second test at McLean Park. Rahul Dravid was on 21 while Sachin Tendulkar was on nought at stumps after nightwatchman Ishant Sharma, who came in when Gautam Gambhir was dismissed for 16, was trapped leg before by skipper Daniel Vettori for a duck in the penultimate over. The dangerous Virender Sehwag was the first wicket to fall when he was caught behind by Brendon McCullum off Vettori for 34, a ball after he had smashed the spinner for six. Gambhir, who survived a close run out call, threw his wicket away when he should have been circumspect, failing to clear Vettori at mid-on against off-spinner Jeetan Patel with six overs remaining in the day's play. New Zealand's massive score was courtesy of Ryder's 201, his first test double century, Brendon McCullum's 115 and contributions from Vettori (55) and James Franklin (52). Ryder had shared a record 271-run partnership with Ross Taylor (151) on Thursday. India lead the three-match series 1-0 after their 10-wicket victory in Hamilton last w
